The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Probably.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all the services as their Western European partners.
However, here we still lack something - the virtual operator, which would force those to be cheaper.
It's probably not going to take long to arrive.
That Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe, we have already written it on mobil.cz.
The rest was also confirmed by the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), which warned that the price of SMS messages in our country is among the most expensive in the entire Union.
After the last steps of the European Commission in the field of regulation of roaming rates is likely to arrive at a paradoxical situation – for some customers of Czech mobile operators the SMS they send from abroad will be cheaper than if they send them from home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic remain so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, lack of competition that you really want to fight.
This probably seems paradoxical to us, as we have three mobile networks and its high coverage is more than 100%.
On the contrary, mobile operators like to complain that there is extreme competition in the Czech market.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99><0xC3><0xA1>k, President of the Czech Telecommunications Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), also said that there is no longer a place in the Czech Republic for any other operator.
It is perhaps true that for a classical operator with his own network he no longer has too many possibilities (for the rest, it would be quite difficult to find some frequency).
However, there is still a possibility - the virtual operator.
It was precisely the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market that brought a sharp drop in prices to which the classical operators had to react.
At the same time, even before sharks such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile entered the UK market, similar voices were heard both there and here.
It has been shown that there is room for this type of operators and that they can be successful.
You don’t have to look too far for examples.
In February this year we inform you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
Only after half a year, this operator managed to get more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator in the neighboring country.
On the other hand, behind Mobilking is the Penta group which, in addition, is the owner of U:fon in the Czech Republic.
The advantage of virtual operators is the possibility of focusing on many more specific target groups.
In addition, in order for them to function effectively, they only need a lot less customers than a classic operator.
They do not carry with them relatively large expenses in the construction, operation and maintenance of the network.
In the world, this type of virtual operators usually profile themselves with low costs - they offer cheap calls and SMS messages that however often counteract the offer of more adjusted services.
Thus, for example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half as cheap as compared to the competition.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, it can also be a good hit to bet on a trivial nothing target group.
This operator is directed specifically to the man.
“The right man chooses Mobilking – it’s the operator he likes and who he can rely on,” says David Seibert, the CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, who works with this virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether such a concept as Poland could engage in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> said: “The Czech market is relatively small to access by segments on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, from the point of view of the offer of services it is relatively saturated"
In the Czech Republic there are no possibilities, say mobile operators
However, it seems almost certain that if there will be a virtual operator in the Czech Republic that will not be Mobilking.
“We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, however, in the Czech Republic it does not seem too hopeful.
Rather, it’s about the launch of Mobilking in other countries in our region,” Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>kov<0xC3><0xA1>, a spokesman for the Penta financial group, said in a telephone conversation for mobil.cz.
He indirectly assured that the current mobile operators in the Czech Republic definitely did not bow to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything possible so that no potential competition arises.
Interest in the launch of a virtual mobile operator already shows the GTS Novara group that would like to take a step further to become a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of business customers.
"We have a great interest in this, in order to offer our customers not only fixed telephone services but also mobile telephone services.
And the sooner, the better.
With this possibility we have met repeatedly with all Czech mobile operators.
With some of them we have made progress in the meetings,” said the group’s spokesman, Pavel Kaidl.
So, maybe they're flashing better times.
It seems that, according to unofficial information, the first official operator would probably have to arrive by the end of the year.
But for now his appearance is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment we believe that the situation is suitable for the emergence of a virtual operator in the Czech market.
The Czech market compared to others is a very specific market.
To date, no one has addressed us with any complex and serious project in this area,” Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88>, spokesman for Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2, told mobil.cz.
Other operators refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-mobile spokesman Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1>, in exceptional compliance with O2’s opinion, adds: “To date, we have not registered any viable commercial projects that, bilaterally beneficial, can continue to develop.”
“On the T-Mobile network, it will be difficult to find any virtual operator by the end of the year.
At this time we should already have on the table some concrete contract that would be possible to study in such a short time frame."
Vodafone directs its attention rather to meeting the own requirements of a 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> adds: "We are open to negotiations with potential virtual operators, and this in terms of cost and infrastructure allocation.
We regard it as the greatest contribution from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this field lies in the partner with whom to establish a shared network for a fast internet on mobile.”
Responsible offices - with nail and meat operators
The progress of mobile operators can be easily understood, but the entry of another operator would mean increasing competition which would lead to a drop in prices and thereby a decrease in profits.
So why make it easier to enter the competition?
When operators want to get something, they are able to pull from the same rope, proof of this is the grab when U:fon emerged.
Perhaps the greatest pressure on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> was at the time of the entry of U:fon by the T-Mobile company.
This is evidenced by the public information accessible on the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> websites.
But right now U:fon serves as an argument for why not accept a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> adds: “Furthermore, not long ago the competitive environment in the mobile phone market was open to a fourth operator.
As far as the nature of the mobile phone market in the Czech Republic is concerned, it is natural that the entry of another player into the market would pose great demands for him and, above all, for his services."
This is why this access to mobile operators is tremendously discouraging due to the absolute disinterest of the Czech regulatory body.
It is not just the attitude of the <0xC4><0x8C>TU, which unfortunately has no competence to intervene in commercial tenders, unlike Britain and other developed countries.
This belongs purely to the Office for the Protection of Commercial Bids (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
However, it expressed its typical stance on this issue.
“The entry of a virtual operator into the mobile phone market would be possible after an agreement was concluded on the rental of the necessary infrastructure between a mobile operator and a virtual operator.
To date, no agreement has been concluded as the offer of potential stakeholders was rather not interesting enough for classical operators,” added Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa, from the UOHS Department of Foreign Affairs.
These statements did not surprise the representatives of the operators.
For offices that must represent the interests of consumers it is more than a consideration, apart from this they must observe that no one takes advantage of their position in the market.
Especially when Kristi<0xC3><0xA1>n Chalupa adds: "In abroad where virtual operators work normally we can see that their entry into the market contributed to the price drop of mobile phone services"
Obviously, the pressure on the proper functioning of the market media and the price drop do not fall within the interest of the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
The really shocking thing in all of this is the dissonant reactions that result from the three mobile operators.
The question of whether it really is a coincidence is offered on its own.
It is the same as with the price of gasoline in petrol stations because it is clear that it is a work of chance and a hard struggle for competition.
"The Office in this regard has found no signs of unfair competition and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators have a dominant position therefore they do not have a corresponding rise in liability in their actions on the market.
The tools needed to open the mobile phone market to virtual operators, rather, are missing, as well as telecommunications regulators,” Chalupa added.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many conflicting points.
Obviously, there is a relevant market analysis drawn up by the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> according to which telecommunications are from the point of view of commercial tendering as a single market.
In this type of market of course none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some of the legal experts offer another view - in order for a virtual operator to emerge it is always necessary to agree with the network administrator.
And the mobile phone operator - with all its logic - has the monopoly of its network.
Therefore, in a particular segment it must necessarily be dominant.
And if this argument is not accepted, at least for <0xC3><0x9A>OHS should represent a warning to the fact that three mobile operators rise remarkably similarly.
The current complaints of the interested parties (including the aforementioned GTS Novera company) show that in all negotiations with the operators they clash with many similar impediments.
Carrying responsibility in <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> is a fairly common trick in the field of telecommunications from which the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS washes its hands in all this matter.
We have met with him in similar cases.
Unfortunately, a new amendment to the telecommunications law for the expansion of <0xC4><0x8C>TU's competition in the field of commercial tenders was recently introduced, even though a number of experts promised that the situation would improve.
This must be perfectly known to the representatives of <0xC3><0x9A>OHS, but it is evident that their interests are elsewhere.
It's all right, when no one looks
At the same time, it still inconspicuously works something like a pseudo-virtual operator that in Czech mobile networks already there are a few.
They are companies that put their own prices on mobile phone services that, however, only a part are public.
These are usually companies that are engaged in multi-level marketing.
Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others offer their own mobile services.
Usually only a select few get the price list of these companies.
The magic is that the company, with respect to the operator, acts as a classic business customer of the same by ordering a large number of SIM cards.
As a special customer you will then receive special prices and other offers.
The problem is that trading conditions in all Czech mobile operators prohibit this type of resale.
"If cases such as those cited could be found to be a breach of contract conditions that could result in the end of the collaboration with the given society," Martina Kemrov<0xC3><0xA1> replied to the question about this problem.
But it is quite unlikely that such an activity carried out by mobile operators would not reach people responsible.
It is precisely in the case of the three companies mentioned that they can be thousands of customers.
None of the operators are against this procedure.
With the activities of these companies they get no negligible profits and at the same time – unlike authentic virtual operators – in no way threaten their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> warns us of possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, however, the services of this company are used only by a negligible so many percent of customers.
These, in addition, must accept that your phone’s SIM card is not in your name so they can’t absolutely dispose of it as a normal carrier customer.”
This is exactly what the <0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A> should look like.
In addition, a new question appears for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators surround the eyes in this type of procedure, why do they block the entry of the virtual operator?
It is necessary to add that the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS has enough competence to discover this type of activities and if you do not want it you should not be satisfied with the explanations of the operators that they have no idea of this story and that their trading conditions do not allow it.
When will we stop being the most expensive
As already made clear in the text, the entry of the virtual operator into the mobile phone market brought a significant drop in the prices of services.
At the same time, in virtually all countries where the virtual operator emerged, the classical operators tried more or less to protect themselves from this disruption.
The arguments used by these were virtually all identical - too small, a market, eventually, too saturated, problems with the quality of service, etc.
In the most advanced countries, however, regulators have intervened and in none of the cases defended operators but their customers.
Whether it was with formal measures or informal pressure, the first virtual operator emerged and with it began to emerge more.
Unfortunately, the Czech Regulatory Body all this case happens as if it were a burning nail.
From our experience we can not fail to be impressed that the confusion of the attributions in these cases suits them.
But let's not despair.
If this behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator actually arrives at these lands, then the Czech mobile market is likely to start moving again.
If any of the operators let a virtual mobile operator enter it will be difficult for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And we may stop calling it more expensive than the rest of Europe.
