Talk about sleeping.
Some children talk at night.
I am not referring to those who wake up very scared telling us something that happened the day before, but to children who talk while they are asleep.
The first time it happens you carry a fear, but it doesn’t really matter.
It is a benign alteration of sleep called somniloquios.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure more than one person has been told that he spoke at night.
This phenomenon can appear very sporadically (once in life for example associated with a high fever episode), or more periodically (every day, once a week, once a month...), the next day the child remembers nothing.
There is no single cause that determines its appearance.
They are often related to other sleep disorders such as nightmares, night terrors, nighttime enuresis (sleeping) or sleepwalking, but it doesn’t have to be that way.
As we have already mentioned above they can also be associated with very high fevers, stress or overexcitation situations.
However, it is a poorly studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also very variable.
It may be that you speak in a calm tone of voice, loose words, a murmur or all the other things (cries, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where the manifestation is very intense it would be advisable to observe the child and consult with a specialist, to check if there is any issue that is generating a lot of anxiety and gives it out in this way.
We have said that it is a benign disorder, therefore it has no treatment, unless it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with sleep apnea or a stress disorder).
What can be done is to take into account a number of very simple preventive measures such as:
Try not to excite the child too much before going to sleep.
So look for quiet games and avoid shows or TV series that are scary or a little violent.
With very nervous children and who find it hard to relax, relaxation techniques can be used to help them acquire a certain inner calm.
This will allow the child to have a quieter sleep.
Once the somnolences appear, try to keep calm.
Remember that they are harmless to the child and that the next day he will remember nothing of what has happened.
Helpful advice
Don't wake him up.
It is useless, because he is not conscious, and you will break his sleep.
Even though he's talking, he's sleeping and so he's resting.
Remember that if you show up very distressed during several episodes it would be good to consult or find out what is causing so much anxiety in the child.
If you understand what he says (which is not the most common), don’t fall into the temptation to ask him for information.
You won’t get anything, because when you’re asleep you’re not aware of how to organize your thinking.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he is dreaming of saying that, so be very careful in how you interpret the information and with the conclusions you draw.
Never tell the child that you can question him at night to find out his secrets.
Not even a joke.
That generates a lot of anxiety.
In short, don’t worry, it’s not a bad thing, it’s an episode that lasts only a few minutes.
