The interview - Blood is safe again
Héma-Québec celebrated its 10th anniversary of its foundation yesterday, and its president, Francine Décary, was right to rejoice, because Héma-Québec has become one of the safest and most effective blood suppliers in the world.
And above all, it regained the public’s confidence that it had been seriously rocked by the contaminated blood scandal in the 1980s and 1990s.
As is known, the national blood reserves administered by the Canadian Red Cross Blood Transfusion Service have been contaminated by the Human Immunodeficiency Virus (HIV) and the hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In the face of this drama and public dissatisfaction, the Government of Canada conducted a public survey in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horacio Krever, which aimed to clarify the circumstances that had led to such a tragedy and to make recommendations for such a disaster not to be repeated again.
While Judge Krever was late in presenting his relationship, certain provinces then set up a committee that aimed to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Quebec, the Gélineau Committee fulfilled this mission.
As a result of the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers have been created in Canada: Héma-Québec to supply Quebec and the Canadian Blood Society to supply all other provinces and both territories.
" In 1998, when Héma-Québec started its activities, nearly 38% of people still had confidence in the blood system in Quebec, Décary recalls.
The situation was discouraging.
Having made a lot of efforts to improve the safety of blood products and a lot of work over the years that followed, we have regained public confidence,” he says before proudly stating that at the beginning of 2008, about 94 percent of the Quebec population had confidence in Héma-Québec.
Dr. Décary recalls, however, that "trust is something extremely fragile".
Since its inception on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
At that time, we were witnessing in Europe the birth of numerous cases of the human variant of mad cow disease, a new variant of Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, Décary says.
And we didn't know if this disease could be transmitted by blood.
Then we rely on one of the main recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which when we do not know and when a serious illness can stem from that, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by a degeneration of the brain that inevitably leads to death, we instituted exclusion measures.
In April 1999, we denied the blood of people who had remained in the UK for more than a month since 1980.
But, a few years ago, it has been proven beyond doubt that this disease is transmitted by blood.
This episode showed us so that the precautionary principle that was applied made sense.”
In 1999 a much more sensitive HIV detection technique appeared on the market: nucleic acid tests that allow directly in the blood of donors to detect the presence of the virus and not that of antibodies against the virus, on which the tests used so far were based.
Nucleic acid tests allowed to shorten the period between the time the person has been infected and the time when the first viruses can be detected in the blood by our techniques, she explains.
We were able to reduce this period in less than a week.
In this way, we substantially reduce the risk that certain donors will be infected without knowing it and that we cannot detect them.
These improvements allowed to significantly lower the risk of contracting AIDS by a blood transfusion.
Today, one in 12 million people are at risk of receiving HIV-infected blood.
"That means that 12 million blood products will have to be distributed before someone is infected with HIV.
So since Héma-Québec distributes between 400,000 and 500,000 blood products each year, it will be more than 24 years before a case of HIV transmission by a blood product occurs.
I think it is possible today to receive or prescribe a blood transfusion to recover health without worries,” says the head of the Héma-Québec administration.
“Our challenge for the next decade is to maintain the safety of our products.
It is never known which pathogen could emerge in the system.
Last year, the Chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Reunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted by an insect in the blood.
It must be constantly vigilant,” Dr. Décary pursues before stressing that in addition to a safe supply, Héma-Québec must also provide sufficient supply.
“Needs are increasing because the population is aging.
Since anti-cancer treatments are more aggressive, patients often need an injection of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has consequences on the network of blood donors that regroups on average only 3% of Quebecers eligible for blood donation.”
All people with good health, 18 years old and who meet the eligibility criteria can still donate blood every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer their blood are not accepted because they suffer from AIDS or malaria, for example, and if they travel to a country where malaria reigns, they will be excluded for a period of one year.
" With this 3%, we managed to maintain an inventory that covers the needs of hospitals.
The pains are very rare.
But you have to renew the members of this donor network as they age and can no longer donate their blood.
But it’s hard to convince people to donate their blood, but above all to retain them and encourage them to be regular donors.
Since current life is very rampant, we rarely find time to spend an hour donating her blood,” says Francine Décary.
With a budget of $297 million annually, Héma-Québec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissues, including bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs and skin that is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analyzed, transformed and frozen before being stored in Hema-Québec, which also manages the only public blood bank of the umbilical cord in Quebec.
The umbilical cord that was once considered as biomedical waste is filled with a blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases such as leukemia.
“We celebrated a few weeks ago, putting on the bench of our thousandth blood sample of the umbilical cord and is expected to bring out more than a thousand of these per year.
We’d have to start proposing it for grafts early next year,” says Dr. Décary, who describes this cord blood-taking program as very popular.
“Many mothers are disappointed that they cannot enjoy this,” as Héma-Québec has no resources to propose this complex and expensive program in all hospitals in Quebec.
