Free opinion - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Speech
In its September 17 issue, Le Devoir published a letter from Mr. Patrick J. Garver, vice president and director of Canadian miner Barrick Gold.
Following Orwellian logic, Barrick Gold claims that the world’s largest gold company attempted a six-million-euro defamation lawsuit against three authors and a small publishing house in order to provoke a “transparent public debate.”
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, it is not the truth they judge, especially in the case of defamation prosecutions, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, this fundamental difference is completely hidden by Mr. Garver.
Why, according to Barrick Gold, would the best way to conduct a public debate be to harm anyone who dares to hold a position contrary to his own?
The outcome of the lawsuit is of little importance, and the authors and publisher of the Noir Canada book will have to spend considerable sums in order to prepare their defense and to fight, with very unequal weapons, against an army of lawyers held by the almost bottomless pockets of the mine.
The tactic, in these unequal struggles, is often to ruin the defendants in order to impose a friendly arrangement that will cushion the opposition in addition to scaring anyone who dares to re-examine the issue.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it is in front of public opinion that he would have had to present his view of the facts.
Contrary to what is done in several countries where Barrick Gold works, debates in Canada are usually done by changing ideas and not by garrot strikes.
It was enough for the mine to open its books, its records and establish a real debate, through the newspapers, the media, the publications and the financing of independent search teams that could have clarified the issue.
But Barrick Gold does not seem to trust public opinion and rejects the petitions and supporting letters to the authors of Noir Canada.
Could Mr. Garver possibly explain how he can ask for a “public” debate by disregarding his views?
According to the Vice-President, this word appears to refer only to highly paid lawyers and not to all Canadians; that represents a very limited view of the concept.
In democracy, detractors also have the right to speak.
What he doesn’t understand – or what he doesn’t want to understand – Barrick Gold, is that the public who supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada does it mainly because it rejects the brutal way of mining.
This audience is willing to listen to Barrick and judge him, but on the basis of civilized changes of arguments, and not within the framework of what many people perceive as a persecution-bite (persecuting the "public debate," Barrick Gold has just filed a claim with respect to the authors of Noir Canada no longer using it).
In addition to Mr. Garver’s surreal speech, the Barrick Gold process is a direct attack on university freedom of inquiry and truth, essential to all democratic societies.
It denies the right to cite credible sources and to debate facts and interpretations, which represent the basis of intellectual work.
If it is impossible to study and discuss subjects that displease the wealthy companies of this world in a country like Canada, under many persecutions, who can do so?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, he could do so by following the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
You have a right of reply.
The university world, to which we belong, has long known how to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s disproportionate persecution clearly shows that, contrary to what he intends, he has no desire to make a transparent debate.
It’s a loss for the university world, but also for public debate in Canada, and it’s time for governments to put in place devices that limit this kind of abusive persecution.
