Overlapping Psychology: Why Do We Spend More Money?
Auction participants are likely to spend more money and overvalue the product.
Neurologists and economists at the University of New York discovered the neurological – economic bases of this known and seemingly irrational behavior.
According to the study published in the journal Science, people don’t want to lose in competitions like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay even an excessive price.
The scientists tried to establish the neurological scheme of this "game" through experimental auctions.
One of the volunteer groups played lottery, the other participated in an auction and, in the meantime, the functional magnetic resonance imaging system (fMRI) examined the active areas of the brain of the participants in the experiment.
In both games participants could earn money, but during the auctions, where it is fundamental to bet more than the other, losing the game intensified the operation of the complex called stratum located under the cerebral cortex.
This area of the brain, in addition to many other functions, plays a role in the “self-prize” mechanism of the nervous system.
Thus, according to scientists, the increase in bets is explained as a prevention so as not to provoke an intense reaction of the stratum.
To base their theory, the economists of the scientific group also conducted a financial follow-up study.
In this experiment, three groups bet against one person in different circumstances.
The control group was simply told the actual value of the product in question, and its members bet.
Another group was also promised that if they won, they would receive $15 more prize.
Instead, the third group received exactly $15 before the auction, but in case of losing the auction, the group members lost even that money.
So the only difference between the two groups was that for one the triumph was highlighted and for the other the failure was highlighted.
However, by testing the neurologists’ hypothesis, the members of the group who played “against failure” were willing to bet even more than the members of the control group and the “winner” group.
“These results cannot be deduced from any previously existing economic theory.
For those so far explained the phenomena of auctions only with the joy of winning and with the prevention of risks.
Only the visual neurological methods helped resolve this contradiction between the two theories, so we now come to a third explanation," said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at the University of New York.
