In the world, about five hundred million people suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C, and in Hungary, chronic liver disease is considered one of the leading causes of death.
The number of people infected in this country is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand receive treatment because many of the patients do not know they are infected.
Hepatitis is the common name for different liver diseases caused by viruses.
The symptoms look very similar; they are characteristic of liver infection and jaundice, but their pathogens and diseases are very different.
Hepatitis viruses depending on the pathogen are spread through two main forms: Hepatitis A and E by food (e.g. with water or contaminated food), Hepatitis B, C, D and other viruses with blood and body humors (sperm, mood of the vagina, saliva).
Travelers are advised to protect themselves against the virus A and B, there are no vaccines against C.
Hepatitis A symptoms appear two to three weeks after consuming the infected food, manifested by a general bad state, weakness, abdominal pain and nausea.
After this appear on the skin and in the white of the eyes jaundice, the excrement becomes clear, dark-colored urine and healing can last even two - three weeks.
Every year, one million people worldwide die from liver cancer and cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B, the most serious forms of this disease.
The main reason for this is that according to the calculations, only one in ten infected people receive pharmacological treatment.
Hepatitis C can also have very serious consequences: without treatment it can produce liver cirrhosis and even cancer.
Most of the infected do not know that they are sick because this pathological agent gradually destroys the liver cells and often the first symptoms appear only 20-30 years later.
Premature recognition, systematic medical control, is therefore very important.
This disease is much more common in three groups: people who had blood transfusion before 1991, drug users and those who carry tattoos.
Currently, there are about 200 million people in the world who suffer from chronic hepatitis C.
As this disease can be discovered with routine laboratory control as well, it is worth consulting with the family doctor when experiencing some unknown symptom.
The disease has healing if it is discovered in time, it is possible to exterminate the virus from the body, so it can suppress the infection and prevent cancer.
30 September is World Hepatitis Day, which was organized for the first time in 2004 by organizations representing the sick.
Its goal is to draw attention to the causes of chronic liver infections caused by viruses and the importance of their early recognition.
Does it hurt less who believes in God?
According to the result of a recent investigation, the religious faith has a calming effect that also alleviated the death of the martyrs of Catholicism.
Scientists at the University of Oxford conducted an interesting experiment: they analyzed what religious belief in how it influences human pain – reported the British newspaper Telegraph.
Within the framework of this unique experiment they applied electric shock to 12 Catholic believers and the same number of atheists, while all were looking at a painting of the Virgin Mary.
According to the results, Catholic believers were able to exclude most of their pain.
Thanks to the scanning technique of the human brain, it was verified that Catholic believers were able to activate that part of their brain that is responsible for the regulation of pain.
This experiment is the first of a series of researches in which scientists, philosophers and theologians from the different departments of the University are also involved.
The analysis took place as follows; they fixed a flashing instrument to the patient's left hand, which applied the electric shock.
The researchers asked the participants of the experiment to fix their gaze on two paintings; the Virgin Mary, a work of 17th-century Sassoferrato and the Lady of the Arminum of Leonardo da Vinci of the 15th-century.
The researchers had hoped that the Virgin Mary’s spectacle would provoke a certain religious spirit among the faithful, while they chose Leonardo’s oil because it was not too different from the other, and they thought it had a calming effect.
The patients spent half an hour on an MRI scanner, receiving 20 electrical shocks in four successive parts while observing the religious-themed painting or the other.
The Catholics claimed that when they looked at the Virgin Mary they felt in "security" as "protected" people, "they calmed down and in their heart ruled peace."
Looking at the religious-themed picture, they felt 12 percent less pain than when they looked at Leonardo’s work.
Psychologist Miguel Farias, who also participated in the experiment, thinks that with any image so striking you can achieve a similar effect with atheists too, you just have to find the right image.
“We should find the portrait of a person for whom they feel very positive, like a mother or a father,” the psychologist said.
Anglican bishop Tom Wright celebrated the result of the investigation.
“The exercise of faith should and in many cases really change our personality,” Wright added.
After these formidable results there remains only one question: what effect would it have on the regulation of pain if the Madonna of Leonardo or another painter of her size were shown to the faithful?
Would the vision of a high-quality Virgin Mary yield even better results?
