The smart car imitates the flight of the beekeeper
What would be the best method to develop technologies in order to avoid collisions, if not the imitation of existing obstacle sensors in nature?
For example, the beekeepers.
In a surprising project presented at Japan’s CEATEC, the beehives provided the starting point for Nissan engineers to design the next generation of collision prevention systems.
Nissan, in cooperation with the University of Tokyo, designed the nature-imitating BR23C robotic steering system, which was given the characteristics of the beehives, with the ultimate goal of creating a system that can evade all collisions.
During the flight each beehive creates its own oval private space that actually looks a lot like our safety protective capsule - explained in the exhibition Kazuhhiro Doi, technological director of RP and development and research.
An important role is played by the compound eyes of the beekeepers who are able to see in all directions at an angle of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the composite eyes, the engineers used the laser beam length measurement system.
It identifies obstacles in front of the BR23C within a distance of 2 meters, at a 180-degree angle, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the vehicle's microprocessor that immediately transforms into a maneuver to avoid collision.
In a fraction of seconds the obstacle is identified, then the robot of the vehicle imitating the movements of the beekeepers, modifies the direction by turning the wheels to the extent necessary.
Unlike any existing system today, this maneuver is entirely instinctive.
“If not, the vehicle robot could not react quickly enough to avoid obstacles,” said Toshiyuki Andoh, head of the Mobility Laboratory and the vehicle robot project.
It must react immediately and instinctively, as this technology corresponds to the most vulnerable inner layer of the safety protective capsule, in a layer within which all types of collisions are currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what a beekeeper does to avoid other beekeepers.
This process should be done in an open and closed eye.
However, unlike beekeepers, movement cannot be directed upwards, downwards or diagonally, but can only be two-dimensional and exclusively in the direction of rotation of the wheels.
In this way, instead of the infinite possibilities that exist for the beekeepers to dodge other beekeepers, here they only used rotational movement and acceleration as a possibility for the auto robot.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and higher in energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion batteries.
According to Andoh, the important thing is the instinctive and intelligent reaction and not the ability to process data, much less that of storage.
This apparatus in every second should only process some input signals and react as the case may be.
It is not necessary to store this data or react with an instinctive logic based on the data of the previous maneuvers, so it uses only a few tens of kilobytes of memory.
No memory of gigabytes or megabytes is needed.
This is the first step in developing the technology to immediately evade obstacles, which according to Nissan’s calculations, within ten years will be able to be incorporated into the series-manufactured models.
Another possibility for its application is to incorporate the unit into the GPS satellite navigation system to take the driver to their destination, avoiding the existing obstacles on their way.
