Industrial prices continue to rise
In August 2008, domestic industrial sales prices increased by 0.1 percent compared to last month’s prices and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007’s prices – the Central Bureau of Statistics (KSH) reported.
Industrial export prices rose by 1.1 per cent compared to July 2008 and decreased by 3.9 per cent compared to the previous year.
And as a result of changes in domestic and export prices, industrial production prices increased by 0.7 percent compared to the previous month and by 3.2 percent compared to the previous year.
Industrial sales prices only increased by a minimum of 0.1 percent.
Internal sales prices in the processing industry sectors rose by a minimum of 0.1 percent compared to the month of July.
The biggest increase in price volume occurred in August 2008, in the leather and footwear production sector (2.8 percent), due primarily to the 4.6 percent monthly increase in bags and belts and the 2.5 percent increase in footwear.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical base materials resulted in a significant monthly increase in the prices of the chemical production branch (1.6 percent).
There was a decrease in price in the petrochemical sector, (1.4 percent), in the production of electric machines and instruments (0.9 percent), as well as - to a minimum - in the wood processing sectors (0.1 percent).
The prices of papermaking, publishing and printing did not change.
In the rest of the sectors of the processing industry there was an increase in prices between 0.2 and 0.9 percent.
In the supply of electricity, gas, heat and water that represent a significant weight within domestic trade, an increase of 0.3 percent was recorded in August, primarily as a result of the effect of the increase in official prices from the first of July.
In a 12-month period - in national sales of the processing industry sectors - the largest increase in prices was recorded in the petrochemical sector (32.4 percent).
In the metal processing sector, there was a 13.2 percent increase, while in the food, beverage and tobacco industry, of decisive weight, there was an 11 percent increase.
There was a decrease in prices in the textile industry (2.5 percent), as well as in the manufacture of electric machines and instruments (0.3 percent).
In the rest of the processing sectors, the rate of price growth was between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Over the past year in the processing industry globally, prices have risen by 10.2 percent.
Prices of electricity, gas, heat and water exceeded prices of the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In August, among the different sectors of domestic trade, the largest monthly price increase (0.7 percent) was recorded in the investment goods sectors.
In the consumer goods sectors, prices increased by 0.3 per cent, in the prices of the energy sector and the intermediate sectors there were no changes compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, compared to the same month of the previous year, the highest price increases occurred in the energy sectors and the intermediate industry (16.8 per cent).
In the consumer goods producing branches, a decrease of 6.8 per cent and in investment goods by 1.4 per cent was recorded.
Industry export prices calculated in HUF increased by 1.1 percent compared to the previous month, and compared to 12 months, there was a decrease of 3.9 percent.
The price of our national currency in one month decreased by 1.7 percent against the euro and by 7.1 percent against the dollar, compared to August 2007 it strengthened by 7.5 percent against the euro and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
