Krugman is one of the biggest critics of the Bush administration’s decisions regarding the economy and foreign policy.
A few months after the September 11, 2001 attack, in those days that Enron broke down, Krugman had predicted in an editorial published by the New York Times that the second event would be more decisive than the first, in terms of consequences for the United States.
A prediction that triggers a lot of controversy and that for several years was blamed on the economy, but that has now turned out to be accurate.
“I’m surprised and a little upset that the memory of the Enron and Worldcom collapse scandal has quickly disappeared from public attention,” Krugman said at the end of 2002.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi, of the European Central Bank’s executive committee, Krugman is a “high-value economist,” but also a publicist with a “very aggressive style, particularly critical of the excesses of the liberalism of the Bush administration.”
