Farewell to the old cinema Paradise, the cities cancel the historic rooms
The historical cinemas close in favor of the Multiplex.
“A city without movie theaters in a blind city is like a face without eyes.”
The image offered by the director Giuseppe Tornatore effectively captures what is happening in the large Italian urban centers and also in the provincial cities.
The process of marginalization of cinemas, which with the birth of the great meticons on the periphery and the consequent disappearance of the mono rooms in the central areas of the city, is an inevitable and indisputable event with all the characteristics of a true cultural crime.
They are almost always historical places, full of memory,"it's as if a friend, a acquaintance with whom a piece of place was shared and so much emotion", observes the director of the new cinema Paradiso, the film that twenty years ago won the cousin Oscar and the grand jury prize in Cannes, which always counted for the poetry of a cinema of a cinema.
The figures given by the Anec, the main association of traders, speak clearly: in the last five years have closed 316 traditional cinemas, and to pay the most are mainly the rooms of the main cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin and 5 in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by the closures are Emilia-Romagna with 82 fewer cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
It is a demonstration that the person responsible for its disappearance is the advent of the multiplex, these three Italian regions have registered the largest number of new methic cinemas: 195 screens more in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in Tuscany than in Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian exercise has developed irrationally,” notes Paolo Protti, president of the Anec, “it would be useful for new structures to be built but it would be necessary to guarantee the permanence of those already existing, because when a city hall closes, not all of its fans are willing to transfer to the meticons.
Not to mention the lack of funds in favor of traders: the state’s previous debt is approximately 10 million euros.
It is shameful from an ethical and moral point of view that the government does not respect existing laws.
To support the sector would serve between 16 and 18 million euros a year.”
Interestingly, the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to worry about the closures, decided to repair itself with the signing of a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to promote and protect the cinema mono room in the historical center as well as in the periphery.
Among the planned rules, there are mediums of tax facilitation for managers and benefits for the public in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the restricted traffic area and will have special rates for parking.
“It’s an initiative I like,” notes Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna’s example by setting other measures.
It is true, that to contrast the extra power of the meticons, the traditional rooms have to improve the quality of sound and image because the public today is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a topic that was always important to me: the closure of the cinema of Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to perform the "New Paradise cinema", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have been living in Rome for 25 years, and when I pass through the already closed Rialto or the Quirinale via Nazionale, where I have lived so many shared emotions, so as not to see the signs blackened by the dust, I turn to the other side.”
